---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---
<Base
  title="PalmasMesh"
  description="A neighbor-run radio network for Palmas del Mar. Like a group chat that works with no Internet, no cell towers, and no monthly fee — built for when the next storm knocks everything else out."
>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-bg" aria-hidden="true">
      <span class="ring r1"></span>
      <span class="ring r2"></span>
      <span class="ring r3"></span>
      <span class="node-core"></span>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap hero-inner">
      <p class="eyebrow">Palmas del Mar · Humacao, Puerto Rico</p>
      <h1>When the towers go down, <span class="hl">we stay in touch.</span></h1>
      <p class="lede">
        PalmasMesh is a <strong>free</strong> community messaging network that runs on small &ldquo;mesh&rdquo; radios
        instead of the cell network. It&rsquo;s built on the open
        source <a href="https://meshtastic.org">Meshtastic</a> protocol — think of it like a
        neighborhood group chat that keeps working with <strong>no Internet, no cell
        towers, and no monthly fee.</strong>
      </p>
      <div class="hero-cta">
        <a href="/hardware/" class="btn btn-primary">Get on the mesh →</a>
        <a href="/join/" class="btn btn-ghost">How the chat works</a>
      </div>
      <p class="hero-foot">Built by neighbors as a gift to the community. Free to join. Forever.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE HOOK: hurricane / staying connected -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Why this matters</p>
      <h2>You already know how this goes.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        The wind picks up. The power flickers, then quits. A little while later
        the cell signal fades to nothing — and just like that, you can't reach
        your neighbors a few streets over to ask if everyone's okay.
      </p>
      <p>
        After María, that silence lasted for far too long. PalmasMesh exists so
        the next time a storm rolls through, Palmas del Mar still has a way to
        talk to itself — to check on a neighbor, share where the water is rising,
        or just let friends and family know you're safe.
      </p>
      <p>
        It doesn't need the power grid. It doesn't need the Internet. It doesn't
        need a single cell tower. The fixed &ldquo;relay&rdquo; nodes that volunteers are
        installing around Palmas are built to ride out a storm — many run on solar
        panels or big battery backups, so they keep working even with the grid
        down. And the personal radio you carry sips so little power that a phone
        charger tops it off in no time, and a small battery keeps it running for
        days. Together, they silently pass your messages neighbor-to-neighbor
        across the community.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE WHATSAPP ANCHOR -->
  <section class="section section-dark">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="anchor">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The simplest way to picture it</p>
          <h2>It's a group chat that doesn't need the Internet or a cell signal.</h2>
          <p class="lede">
            If you've ever used WhatsApp to keep up with family or a building
            group, you already understand PalmasMesh. You type a message, you
            hit send, your neighbors see it.
          </p>
          <p>
            The only difference is what carries the message. WhatsApp needs the
            Internet. PalmasMesh uses a little radio in your pocket, or even on your
            keychain, and it hops your message from one neighbor's radio to the
            next until it arrives. No account, no phone number required, nothing
            to pay each month.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="compare">
          <div class="compare-row head">
            <span></span><span>WhatsApp</span><span>PalmasMesh</span>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <span>Send & receive group text messages</span><span class="yes">✓</span><span class="yes">✓</span>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <span>Send & receive private direct text messages</span><span class="yes">✓</span><span class="yes">✓</span>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <span>Send & receive pictures and audio messages</span><span class="yes">✓</span><span class="no">✕</span>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <span>Works during a blackout</span><span class="no">✕</span><span class="yes">✓</span>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <span>Works with no cell signal</span><span class="no">✕</span><span class="yes">✓</span>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <span>Works with no Internet</span><span class="no">✕</span><span class="yes">✓</span>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-row">
            <span>Monthly cost</span><span>data plan</span><span class="hl">$0</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- REACH BEYOND / RESILIENCE -->
  <section class="section section-tide">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">A little more reach</p>
      <h2>Local first — but not cut off from the world.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        PalmasMesh works entirely on its own, but we also plan to bridge it to
        the Internet when that's available. So under normal conditions, you can
        reach friends and family well beyond Palmas, too.
      </p>
      <p>
        And here's the reassuring part: even in the worst case — if a storm
        takes out the Internet and knocks down some of our relay nodes — Palmas
        can still talk to itself. Mesh networks are stubbornly resilient: as
        long as enough neighbors are on the air, your messages keep finding
        their way across the community.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- HOW IT WORKS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
      <h2>Three small things, working together.</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-3 how">
        <div class="card">
          <span class="how-step">1</span>
          <h3>A little radio</h3>
          <p>
            You get a small, inexpensive device — generally smaller than a deck of
            cards. It's the radio that does the talking. We'll point you to a
            few good options.
          </p>
          <a href="/hardware/">What to buy →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="how-step">2</span>
          <h3>Your phone</h3>
          <p>
            A free app on your phone connects to the radio over Bluetooth. You
            read and type messages right on your phone, the way you already do.
          </p>
          <a href="/setup/">Set it up →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="how-step">3</span>
          <h3>The neighborhood</h3>
          <p>
            Every radio in Palmas quietly passes messages along for everyone
            else. The more neighbors join, the further the network reaches, and
            the more resilient it becomes in a disaster scenario.
          </p>
          <a href="/join/">Join the chat →</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- EVERYDAY USE / GAMES HINT -->
  <section class="section section-dark everyday">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Not just for emergencies</p>
      <h2>A network you'll actually use on a Tuesday.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        A safety net only helps if it's already up and running when you need it
        — so PalmasMesh is built to be part of everyday life in Palmas, not just
        a break-glass-in-emergency tool.
      </p>
      <p>
        Create your own chat groups. Ask if anyone's heading to the airport.
        Trade a surfboard or a ladder. Coordinate an impromptu poker night. Or
        a pickleball match. And keep an eye out — we're working on community
        games and regular activities right on the mesh, so there's a reason to
        stay connected. The more it's part of the routine, the more ready we
        all are when it counts.
      </p>
      <span class="pill">⬤ Community games & activities — coming soon</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT ELSE / FUTURE USES -->
  <section class="section section-dark future-sec">
    <div class="wrap-narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Down the road</p>
      <h2>Messages today — and a lot more tomorrow.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Once a community has its own radio network, it can carry far more than
        chat. The same little radios that pass your messages can quietly do
        useful jobs in the background — and as PalmasMesh grows, these are some
        of the things we'd love to build with you.
      </p>
      <ul class="future">
        <li><strong>Keep track of things.</strong> A small tag on a boat, a
          golf cart, a pet carrier, or emergency gear, so you can see where it
          is on the map.</li>
        <li><strong>Quiet sensors around Palmas.</strong> Temperature and
          humidity readings, a remote weather station, water-level or flood
          sensors near low spots (or on your boat) — little check-ins that arrive on their own,
          no Internet required.</li>
        <li><strong>Automatic alerts.</strong> A door or gate sensor, a sump-pump
          or generator alarm, or a storm-warning broadcast that reaches everyone
          on the mesh at once — even with the towers down.</li>
        <li><strong>Buttons that just work.</strong> A simple &ldquo;I&rsquo;m okay&rdquo;
          or &ldquo;need help&rdquo; check-in for neighbors who&rsquo;d rather not fuss
          with a phone during an emergency.</li>
        <li><strong>And more over time.</strong> The Meshtastic world is moving
          fast — from off-grid payments to all kinds of small connected devices.
          As good ideas come along, a network that&rsquo;s already up and running is
          ready to carry them.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="future-foot">
        Got an idea, or something you&rsquo;d like to try? <a href="/contact/">Tell us</a> —
        a lot of this gets built because a neighbor asked.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section finalcta">
    <div class="wrap-narrow center">
      <h2>Ready to join your neighbors?</h2>
      <p class="lede">Getting on the mesh takes one small purchase (good options under $50) and about fifteen minutes. We'll walk you through every step.</p>
      <div class="hero-cta center">
        <a href="/hardware/" class="btn btn-primary">See what to buy →</a>
        <a href="/faq/" class="btn btn-dark">Read the FAQ</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    /* Hero */
    .hero {
      position: relative;
      overflow: hidden;
      background:
        radial-gradient(140% 100% at 70% -20%, rgba(255,179,71,0.14), transparent 55%),
        linear-gradient(180deg, var(--abyss), var(--deep));
      color: var(--foam);
      padding: clamp(4rem, 10vw, 8rem) 0 clamp(3.5rem, 8vw, 6rem);
    }
    .hero-inner { position: relative; z-index: 2; max-width: 40rem; }
    .hero h1 { color: var(--foam); margin-bottom: 0.6rem; }
    .hero .hl { color: var(--signal); }
    .hero .lede { color: var(--mist); max-width: 36ch; }
    .hero-cta { display: flex; gap: 0.8rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 2rem; }
    .hero-cta.center { justify-content: center; }
    .hero-foot { margin-top: 1.6rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--mist); }

    /* Signature: a node with signal rings pulsing outward */
    .hero-bg {
      position: absolute;
      top: 50%; right: -6%;
      transform: translateY(-50%);
      width: min(46vw, 520px);
      aspect-ratio: 1;
      z-index: 1;
      pointer-events: none;
    }
    .node-core, .ring {
      position: absolute;
      top: 50%; left: 50%;
      border-radius: 50%;
      transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
    }
    .node-core {
      width: 22px; height: 22px;
      background: var(--signal);
      box-shadow: 0 0 30px 6px rgba(255,179,71,0.5);
    }
    .ring {
      border: 1px solid var(--reef);
      opacity: 0;
      animation: pulse 4.5s ease-out infinite;
    }
    .ring.r1 { width: 120px; height: 120px; animation-delay: 0s; }
    .ring.r2 { width: 120px; height: 120px; animation-delay: 1.5s; }
    .ring.r3 { width: 120px; height: 120px; animation-delay: 3s; }
    @keyframes pulse {
      0%   { opacity: 0.6; transform: translate(-50%,-50%) scale(0.3); border-color: var(--signal); }
      100% { opacity: 0; transform: translate(-50%,-50%) scale(3.6); border-color: var(--reef); }
    }
    @media (max-width: 760px) { .hero-bg { opacity: 0.35; right: -25%; } }
    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) { .ring { display: none; } }

    /* WhatsApp anchor */
    .anchor { display: grid; gap: 2.5rem; align-items: center; }
    @media (min-width: 860px) { .anchor { grid-template-columns: 1.1fr 0.9fr; } }
    .compare {
      background: var(--tide);
      border: 1px solid var(--line-dk);
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      overflow: hidden;
    }
    .compare-row {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1.6fr 0.8fr 0.8fr;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.8rem 1.1rem;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--line-dk);
      font-size: 0.92rem;
    }
    .compare-row:first-child { border-top: 0; }
    .compare-row span:nth-child(2),
    .compare-row span:nth-child(3) { text-align: center; }
    .compare-row.head { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.74rem; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--mist); }
    .compare-row .hl { color: var(--signal); font-weight: 600; }
    .compare-row .yes { color: var(--reef); font-weight: 700; }
    .compare-row .no { color: var(--warn); font-weight: 700; }

    /* How it works */
    .how { margin-top: 2.5rem; }
    .how .card { display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
    .how-step {
      font-family: var(--display);
      font-size: 2.2rem;
      color: var(--signal);
      line-height: 1;
      margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
    }
    .how .card a { margin-top: auto; padding-top: 0.8rem; font-weight: 600; }

    /* Everyday */
    .everyday { background:
      radial-gradient(110% 90% at 10% 110%, rgba(47,182,163,0.12), transparent 55%),
      var(--deep); }
    .everyday .pill { margin-top: 1.2rem; }

    /* Future uses */
    .future-sec { background:
      radial-gradient(120% 90% at 90% -10%, rgba(255,179,71,0.14), transparent 55%),
      var(--abyss); }
    .future {
      margin: 1.6rem 0 0;
      padding: 0;
      list-style: none;
      display: grid;
      gap: 0.9rem;
    }
    .future li {
      position: relative;
      padding-left: 1.9rem;
      max-width: 64ch;
    }
    .future li::before {
      content: "›";
      position: absolute;
      left: 0;
      top: -0.12em;
      font-size: 1.5em;
      line-height: 1;
      color: var(--signal);
      font-weight: 800;
    }
    .future-foot { margin-top: 1.6rem; }

    /* Final CTA */
    .finalcta { background: var(--foam-2); }
    .center { text-align: center; }
    .finalcta .lede { max-width: 48ch; margin-inline: auto; }
  </style>
</Base>
